codewars.a_bubbly_programming_language module¶

Bubbly Programming Language

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.a_bubbly_programming_language.add(func)[source]¶

This function pops the top two items from the top of the stack, sums them together, and then puts the result on the top of the stack.

Parameters:

func – The function to call after this function

Returns:

The function to call. If the function to call is end(), the result of that function is returned.

codewars.a_bubbly_programming_language.div(func)[source]¶

This function pops the top two items from the top of the stack, divides the first one that was popped by the second one, and then puts the result on the top of the stack. It is assumed that the second item is not equal to zero.

Parameters:

func – The function to call after this function

Returns:

The function to call. If the function to call is end(), the result of that function is returned.

codewars.a_bubbly_programming_language.end()[source]¶

This function represents the end of a program.

Returns:

The top of the stack

codewars.a_bubbly_programming_language.mul(func)[source]¶

This function pops the top two items from the top of the stack, multiples them together, and then puts the result on the top of the stack.

Parameters:

func – The function to call after this function

Returns:

The function to call. If the function to call is end(), the result of that function is returned.

codewars.a_bubbly_programming_language.start(func)[source]¶

This function represents the start of a program written in the Bubbly programming language. This function clears the stack used in the program.

Returns:

The function to call

codewars.a_bubbly_programming_language.sub(func)[source]¶

This function pops the top two items from the top of the stack, subtracts the second one that was popped from the first one, and then puts the result on the top of the stack.

Parameters:

func – The function to call after this function

Returns:

The function to call. If the function to call is end(), the result of that function is returned.

codewars.adding_values_of_arrays_in_a_shifted_way module¶

Adding Values of Arrays in a Shifted Way

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.adding_values_of_arrays_in_a_shifted_way.sum_arrays(arrays: list[list], shift: int) → list[source]¶

This function shifts all the integers in each sublist of arrays shift * N spaces to the right where N is the index (starting at 0) of the sublist in arrays. After all the integers in a sublist are shifted, they are summed with the integers in the list that is returned. It is assumed that each sublist contains the same number of integers.

Parameters:

  • arrays – A list containing lists of integers

  • shift – The value to shift all the integers in each sublist

Returns:

A list containing sums

codewars.age_range_compatibility_equation module¶

Age Range Compatibility Equation

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.age_range_compatibility_equation.dating_range(age: int) → str[source]¶

This function implements a dating rule for people of all ages. For people who are fifteen years old or older, the minimum age is: (age / 2) + 7, and the maximum age is: (age - 7) * 2. For people who are fourteen years old or younger, a different algorithm is used: age +/- 10% of age.

Parameters:

age – The input integer, a person’s age

Returns:

The socially acceptable age range of the dating partner

To find the median, the list must be sorted first, but a copy of the list will be made before it is sorted, leaving the original list untouched.

codewars.alphabet_war_airstrike_letters_massacre module¶

Alphabet War Airstrike

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.alphabet_war_airstrike_letters_massacre.alphabet_war(fight: str) → str[source]¶

This function replaces letters in the given string with underscores if they are next to a bomb that is represented by an asterisk. The letter immediately before and after the asterisk are each replaced by an underscore. If two asterisks are next to each other, the one on the right will not be replaced by an underscore. Asterisks are processed from left to right.

Parameters:

fight – The input string representing a fight between two factions of letters

Returns:

A string declaring which side won the fight or a stalemate

codewars.alphabet_war_airstrike_letters_massacre.count_sides(fight: str) → str[source]¶

This helper function counts the number of powers of each side and determines whether there is a victor or stalemate.

Parameters:

fight – The fight after an airstrike

Returns:

A string declaring which side won the fight or a stalemate

codewars.alphabetical_grid module¶

Alphabetical Grid

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.alphabetical_grid.grid(number: int) → str | None[source]¶

This function returns a square grid of size number. Each cell in the grid contains an ASCII character between ‘a’ and ‘z’, inclusive. The order goes from ‘a’, ‘b’, ‘c’, … in the first row; ‘b’, ‘c’, ‘d’, … in the second row; etc. After ‘z’, the sequence starts over from ‘a’. If number is negative, None is returned.

Parameters:

number – The size of the square grid, i.e. the number of characters in each row and column

Returns:

A grid of size number by number that contains ASCII characters that are in alphabetical order starting with ‘a’, or None if number is negative

codewars.always_perfect module¶

Always Perfect

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.always_perfect.check_root(string: str) → str[source]¶

This function adds 1 to the product of all the integers in the given string and then takes the square root of the result, which is always a perfect square. If there are more than or less than four integers in the list, “incorrect input” is returned. If there are other characters besides numbers in the list (excluding the commas that separate each integer), “incorrect input” is raised. If the numbers in the string are not consecutive, “not consecutive” is returned. Otherwise, the sum and the square root are returned. For example, given “4,5,6,7”, the string “841, 29” is returned.

Parameters:

string – The input string containing integers separated by commas

Returns:

“incorrect input”, “not consecutive”, or the sum and the square root, as described above

codewars.area_of_a_square module¶

Area of a Square

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.area_of_a_square.square_area(arc_length: int)[source]¶

This function calculates the area of a square given the length of an arc that stretches from one corner of the square to the opposite corner. The formula for calculating the radius of a circle is as follows: radius = arc length / angle (in radians). The radius of the circle is equal to the length of each side of the square. Note that ninety degrees is equal to pi / 2 radians.

Parameters:

arc_length – The arc length of a part of a circle

Returns:

The area of the square

codewars.arithmetic_sequence_sum_of_n_elements module¶

Arithmetic Sequence - Sum of N Elements

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.arithmetic_sequence_sum_of_n_elements.arithmetic_sequence_sum(number: int, constant: int, max_length: int) → int[source]¶

This function produces an arithmetic sequence of integers, i.e. the difference between one element in a list and the next element is constant. The list that is returned will be of size max_length. A ValueError is raised if max_length is less than zero. Each element in the list is the sum of number and the number of occurrences of constant (the number of occurrences is equal to the element’s position in the list, and position numbers start with 0).

Parameters:

  • number – An integer

  • constant – The integer to add zero or more times with number

  • max_length – The maximum number of integers in the arithmetic sequence

Returns:

The sum of the arithmetic sequence

codewars.array_manipulation module¶

Array Manipulation

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.array_manipulation.array_manip(array: list[int]) → list[int][source]¶

This function replaces every element in the given list of integers with one that is to its right and is the least element out of all the elements that are greater than it. If there are no elements to its right that are greater than it, the element is replaced with -1. For example, given [1, 3, 2, 4, 5], [2, 4, -1, 5, -1] is returned.

Parameters:

array – The input list of integers

Returns:

A list of integers that are greater than the ones that they replaced

This function interleaves the elements in arr1 with the elements in arr2. For example, given [1, 3, 5] and [2, 4, 6], [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6] is returned. It is assumed that both lists contain the same number of elements.

Parameters:

  • arr1 – The first input list

  • arr2 – The second input list

Returns:

A list containing elements from both lists

codewars.average_array module¶

Average Array

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.average_array.avg_array(lists: list[list]) → list[source]¶

This function calculates the average of all the elements in each list that are at the same index. For example, given [[1, 2, 3], [4, 2], [1]], the function will return [2.0, 2.0, 3.0] because 1 + 4 + 1 = 6 / 3 = 2.0, 2 + 2 = 4 / 2 = 2.0, and 3 / 1 = 3.0.

Parameters:

lists – The input list that contains lists of numbers

Returns:

A list containing averages

codewars.bits_battle module¶

Bits Battle

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.bits_battle.bits_battle(numbers: list[int]) → str[source]¶

This function counts the number of zeros in all even numbers and the number of ones in all odd numbers. The number zero is not counted. Evens win if the number of ones is greater than the number of zeros, odds win if the number of zeros is greater than the number of ones, and a tie if both numbers are the same.

Parameters:

numbers – The input list of integers

Returns:

A string stating the winner or a tie

This helper function shortens the given URL string if it contains more than 30 characters. If it does contain more than 30 characters, the first letter of each word that is not in the ignore_words list is used to generate the display text for the breadcrumb. If the URL string contains 30 characters or less, all hyphens are replaced by spaces, and all letters in each word are turned to uppercase.

Parameters:

string – The URL string to shorten

Returns:

A shortened URL string if it originally contained more than 30 characters

codewars.broken_sequence module¶

Broken Sequence

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.broken_sequence.find_missing_number(sequence: str) → int[source]¶

This function checks whether the given sequence of integers contains non-numeric characters or is missing a number. If the sequence of integers, starting from 1 and increasing by 1, is not missing a number or the sequence is empty, 0 is returned. If non-numeric characters are present, 1 is returned. If the sequence is missing numbers, the lowest number that is missing is returned. For example, given “1 2 6”, the missing numbers are 3, 4, and 5, so 3 is returned.

Parameters:

sequence – A whitespace-delimited sequence of integers

Returns:

0, 1, or N where N is the lowest number that is missing in sequence

codewars.by_3_or_not_by_3_that_is_the_question module¶

Divisible by Three

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.by_3_or_not_by_3_that_is_the_question.divisible_by_three(string: str) → bool[source]¶

This function returns True if the given number is divisible by three without using the modulo operator. All the digits in the number are summed together. If the length of the sum is greater than one, the process is repeated. The original number is divisible by 3 if the final sum is 3, 6, or 9.

Parameters:

string – The number as a string

Returns:

True if the original number is divisible by 3, False otherwise

codewars.calculator module¶

Calculator

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

class codewars.calculator.Calculator[source]¶

Bases: object

This class contains one static method that will solve a basic arithmetic equation. The equation is assumed to only contain (, ), asterisk, /, +, and -.

static evaluate(string)[source]¶

This method solves the equation in string, keeping in mind the order of operations, that is, parentheses first, followed by multiplication and division, and finally addition and subtraction.

Parameters:

string – An equation

Returns:

A float or an int, the result of solving the equation

codewars.calculator.math_op(equation, idx, equation_list)[source]¶

Using the operator in equation_list, this helper function performs the appropriate math operation.

Parameters:

  • equation – The equation

  • idx – The index of the math operator in equation_list

  • equation_list – A list containing the math operator and operands

Returns:

A string representing the result of the math operation

codewars.calculator.perform_math_ops(equation: str)[source]¶

This helper function solves the given equation, first performing multiplication and division from left to right and then addition and subtraction also from left to right

Parameters:

equation – The basic arithmetic equation to solve

Returns:

A number, the result of solving the equation

codewars.calculator.solve(equation: str)[source]¶

This helper function formats the given equation before it is solved by perform_math_ops(), namely, making sure that the minus sign, if it comes after another math operator such as the multiplication operator, has no space after it, i.e. making the number following the minus sign negative.

Parameters:

equation – The equation

Returns:

The result of performing all the math operations in equation

codewars.calculator.str_to_list(string: str) → list[str][source]¶

This helper function converts the given string to a list. If a number has more than one digit, the entire number will be concatenated together before being put in the resulting list.

Parameters:

string – A string containing numbers and math operators

Returns:

A list representation of the string

codewars.catching_car_mileage_numbers module¶

Catching Car Mileage Numbers

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.catching_car_mileage_numbers.is_interesting(number: int, awesome_phrases: list[int]) → int[source]¶

This function returns 2 if number, which represents the mileage on an odometer, is an “interesting number”, 1 if the “interesting number” is a mile or two miles ahead, or 0 if number is not an “interesting number”. A number is “interesting” if one of the following is true: the number has one digit [1-9] followed by all zeros (e.g. 20000), the number contains the same digits (e.g. 7777), the digits in the number are increasing (e.g. 1234), the digits in the number are decreasing (e.g. 9876), the number is a palindrome (e.g. 12321), or the number matches any of the numbers in awesome_phrases. For sequences that are increasing, the digit 0 must come after 9, and for sequences that are decreasing, the digit 0 must come after 1. Only numbers greater than 99 are considered “interesting”.

Parameters:

  • number – The input integer representing mileage on an odometer

  • awesome_phrases – A list of integers, may be empty

Returns:

0, 1, or 2

codewars.check_if_a_triangle_is_an_equable_triangle module¶

Check if a Triangle is an Equable Triangle

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.check_if_a_triangle_is_an_equable_triangle.equable_triangle(side_a: int, side_b: int, side_c: int) → bool[source]¶

This function returns True if the perimeter of a triangle is equal to its area. Such rectangles are called equable triangles. Note that the formula for calculating the area of a triangle is not 0.5 * side_a * side_b. Instead, it uses the formula for calculating the area of Heronian triangles.

Parameters:

  • side_a – The input integer representing the length of side A

  • side_b – The input integer representing the length of side B

  • side_c – The input integer representing the length of side C

Returns:

True if the perimeter and area are equal, False otherwise

codewars.check_if_a_triangle_is_an_equable_triangle.heronian_triangle_formula(side_a: int, side_b: int, side_c: int) → float[source]¶

This helper function calculates the area of a Heronian triangle, which is a triangle that has side lengths and an area that are all integers. The perimeter of such a triangle is always even, and there is at most one side that has an even length.

Parameters:

  • side_a – The length of side A

  • side_b – The length of side B

  • side_c – The length of side C

Returns:

The area of a Heronian triangle

This class represents a circular list. A call to next() when the cursor is on the last element will move the cursor to the first element, and a call to prev() when the cursor is on the first element will move the cursor to the last element.

The next element in the list

prev()[source]¶

Returns the previous element in the list. If the cursor is on the first element, the last element is returned.

Returns:

The previous element in the list

This function checks whether the given word is “comfortable”. That is, the hands alternate when a word is typed on a QWERTY keyboard. For example, “cub” is a comfortable word because the left hand types “c”, then the right hand types “u”, and finally the left hand types “b”, but “wand” is not a comfortable word because the left hand types the first two characters.

codewars.composing_squared_strings module¶

Composing Squared Strings

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.composing_squared_strings.compose(string_1: str, string_2: str) → str[source]¶

This function generates a string from two squared strings. Both string_1 and string_2 are squared strings. A squared string contains the same number of lines as the number of characters on each line. This function generates a string that contains N lines, each line containing N + 1 characters. To generate this string, the first line will contain the first character from string_1 and all the characters from string_2, the second line will contain the first two characters from string_1 and all the characters of the penultimate line of string_2 except the last character, and so on until the last line will contain all the characters from string_1 and the first character of the first line of string_2.

Parameters:

  • string_1 – The first input string, a squared string of size N

  • string_2 – The second input string, a squared string of size N

Returns:

A string that contains N lines, each line containing N + 1 characters, as described above

codewars.compoundarray module¶

CompoundArray

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.compoundarray.compound_array(arr1: list, arr2: list) → list[source]¶

This function returns a list in which the elements of one list are interleaved with the elements in another list. For example, given [1, 2, 3, 4, 5] and [9, 8, 7], [1, 9, 2, 8, 3, 7, 4, 5] is returned. Each element in arr2 is inserted at an odd index in the list that is returned.

Parameters:

  • arr1 – The first input list

  • arr2 – The second input list

Returns:

A list that contains elements from both arr1 and arr2

codewars.csv_representation_of_array.to_csv_text(array: list[list]) → str[source]¶

codewars.decipher_student_messages module¶

Decipher Student Messages

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.decipher_student_messages.decipher_message(message: str) → str[source]¶

This function decodes the given message that was encoded using a grid whose length and width is the square root of the length of message. The original message was written from left to right starting from the top left of the grid. The message wrapped to the next line until the last character of the message is at the bottom right of the grid. The message was encoded by concatenating the characters together starting from the top to the bottom one column at a time.

Parameters:

message – The input string, the message to decode

Returns:

The decoded message

codewars.ean_validation module¶

EAN Validation

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.ean_validation.validate_ean(code: str) → bool[source]¶

This function validates the given European Article Number (EAN) barcode. The barcode is thirteen digits long. Each digit in the even position of the 12-digit data portion of the barcode is multiplied by 1, and each digit in the odd position is multiplied by 3. The two results are summed together. If the sum is a multiple of 10, the checksum is zero. Otherwise, the checksum is 10 - (sum modulo 10). If the checksum matches the last (13th) digit in the barcode, True is returned. If they do not match or the barcode is not thirteen digits long, False is returned.

Parameters:

code – The EAN barcode to validate

Returns:

True if the barcode is valid, False otherwise

Parameters:

book – The input string representing a checkbook

Returns:

The checkbook with all invalid characters removed and including the total and average expenses

codewars.evaluate_mathematical_expression module¶

Evaluate Mathematical Expression

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.evaluate_mathematical_expression.calc(expression: str)[source]¶

This function evaluates the given mathematical expression and returns the result as an integer or a float. The expression can consist of addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, and parentheses. Numbers may be whole numbers (e.g. 10) or decimal numbers (e.g. 7.25). Operators are always evaluated from left to right, and multiplication and division are evaluated before addition and subtraction. Multiple levels of parentheses are supported, e.g. ((2 + (((5))))). Whitespaces between numbers and operators are also supported. Finally, the minus sign (hyphen) used for negating numbers and parentheses will never be separated by whitespaces. For example, “6 + -(4)” and “6 + -( -4)” are valid expressions whereas “6 + - (4)” and “6 + -(- 4)” are invalid.

Parameters:

expression – The input string, a valid mathematical expression

Returns:

The result of the mathematical expression as an integer or a float

codewars.evaluate_mathematical_expression.calculate(expression: list) → list[source]¶

This helper function evaluates the given mathematical expression and returns the result. The expression can contain zero, one, or more mathematical operators. Operator precedence is followed.

Parameters:

expression – The mathematical expression to evaluate

Returns:

The result of the mathematical expression

codewars.evaluate_mathematical_expression.perform_op(first_number, second_number, operator: str)[source]¶

This helper function performs a mathematical operation and returns the result.

Parameters:

  • first_number – The first number

  • second_number – The second number

  • operator – A character representing multiplication (‘*’), division (‘/’), subtraction (‘-‘), or addition (‘+’)

Returns:

The result of the mathematical operation

codewars.evaluate_mathematical_expression.replace_hyphens(expr: list) → list[source]¶

This helper function replaces all the minus signs (hyphens) that are by themselves. For example, [“-”, “5”] and [“5”, “-”, “-”, “4”] will become [-5] and [“5”, “+”, 4], respectively. Another example: [“-”, “7”, “+”, “-”, “3”, “-”, “-1”] will become [-7, “+”, -3, “+”, 1].

Parameters:

expr – A mathematical expression

Returns:

The same expression but with all separate hyphens replaced

codewars.exclamation_marks_series_number_12_remove_odd_number_continuous_exclamation_marks_and_question_marks module¶

Exclamation Marks Series #12: Remove Odd Number Continuous Exclamation Marks and Question Marks

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.exclamation_marks_series_number_12_remove_odd_number_continuous_exclamation_marks_and_question_marks.remove(string: str) → str[source]¶

This function removes groups that contain an odd number of continuous exclamation marks or question marks. Groups are removed from left to right. After the rightmost group is removed, the process starts over from the beginning of the new string and is repeated until there are no more groups. A group must contain three or more characters; a single character does not count.

Parameters:

string – The input string that contains only exclamation marks and/or question marks

Returns:

A string without groups that contain an odd number of continuous exclamation marks or question marks

codewars.exclamation_marks_series_number_13_count_the_number_of_exclamation_marks_and_question_marks_return_the_product module¶

Exclamation Marks Series #13: Count the Number of Exclamation Marks and Question Marks, Return the Product

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.exclamation_marks_series_number_13_count_the_number_of_exclamation_marks_and_question_marks_return_the_product.product(string: str) → int[source]¶

This function counts the number of exclamation marks and exclamation marks in string and returns the product of both counts.

Parameters:

string – The input string

Returns:

The result of multiplying the number of exclamation marks with the number of question marks

codewars.exclamation_marks_series_number_14_convert_the_exclamation_marks_and_question_marks_to_a_prime_number module¶

Exclamation Marks Series #14: Convert the Exclamation Marks and Question Marks to a Prime Number

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.exclamation_marks_series_number_14_convert_the_exclamation_marks_and_question_marks_to_a_prime_number.convert(string: str) → int[source]¶

This function converts groups of continuous exclamation marks and question marks to a number. If the number is prime, it is returned. Otherwise, the number is divided by the smallest factor. This process is repeated until the number is prime. For example, given “!????!!!?”, the function converts the string to 1431, which is not prime. 1431 // 3 = 477 -> 477 // 3 = 159 -> 159 // 3 = 53, which is prime, so the function returns 53.

Parameters:

string – The input string

Returns:

A prime number

codewars.exclamation_marks_series_number_14_convert_the_exclamation_marks_and_question_marks_to_a_prime_number.is_prime(number: int) → bool[source]¶

This helper function returns True if the given integer is a prime number, False otherwise.

Parameters:

number – The input integer

Returns:

True if the integer is prime, False otherwise

codewars.exclamation_marks_series_number_15_replace_the_pair_of_exclamation_marks_and_question_marks_to_spaces module¶

Exclamation Marks Series #15: Replace the Pair of Exclamation Marks and Question Marks to Spaces

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.exclamation_marks_series_number_15_replace_the_pair_of_exclamation_marks_and_question_marks_to_spaces.replace(string: str) → str[source]¶

This function replaces all pairs of exclamation marks and question marks with spaces. A pair consists of one or more exclamation marks and an equal number of question marks. Both exclamation marks and questions marks do not need to be adjacent to each other. For example, given “??!!!?!!???!!”, the string “ ? !!” is returned. In the example, “??” and “!!” make up one pair, and “!!!” and “???” make up another pair.

Parameters:

string – The input string

Returns:

A string that contains spaces if string contains pairs of exclamation marks and question marks

codewars.exclamation_marks_series_number_16_find_the_longest_successive_exclamation_marks_and_question_marks_combination_in_the_string module¶

Exclamation Marks Series #16: Find the Longest Successive Exclamation Marks and Question Marks Combination in the String

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.exclamation_marks_series_number_16_find_the_longest_successive_exclamation_marks_and_question_marks_combination_in_the_string.find(string: str) → str[source]¶

This function finds the longest combination of exclamation marks and question marks. The combination must contain only two parts: a string consisting of “!” and a string consisting of “?”. Both must be adjacent. If two or more combinations share the same length, the first one that is found is returned. If no combinations are found, an empty string is returned.

Parameters:

string – The input string consisting of only exclamation marks and question marks

Returns:

A combination consisting of exclamation marks and question marks, or an empty string

codewars.exclamation_marks_series_number_17_put_the_exclamation_marks_and_question_marks_on_the_balance_are_they_balanced module¶

Exclamation Marks Series #17: Put the Exclamation Marks and Question Marks on the Balance - Are They Balanced?

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.exclamation_marks_series_number_17_put_the_exclamation_marks_and_question_marks_on_the_balance_are_they_balanced.balance(left: str, right: str) → str[source]¶

This function compares two strings that only contain exclamation marks and/or question marks. An exclamation mark has a weight of two, and a question mark has a weight of three. The sum of all the weights in one string is compared with the sum of all the weights in the other string. If left weighs more, “Left” is returned. If right weighs more, “Right” is returned. If both strings weigh the same, “Balance” is returned.

Parameters:

  • left – The input string

  • right – The input string

Returns:

“Left”, “Right”, or “Balance”

codewars.exponential_golomb_decoder module¶

Exponential-Golomb Decoder

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.exponential_golomb_decoder.decoder(sequence: str) → list[int][source]¶

This function decodes the given binary string that was encoded using an exponential-Golomb code. First, get the number of preceding zeros. Then a substring (that starts with 1) of the binary string that contains that number of bits is converted to a base-10 representation of an integer and lastly decremented by one. This process is repeated until all bits in the encoded binary string are processed.

Parameters:

sequence – The input string, encoded using an exponential-Golomb code

Returns:

The decoded string

codewars.fire_and_fury module¶

FIRE and FURY

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.fire_and_fury.fire_and_fury(tweet: str) → str[source]¶

This function converts the words “FIRE” and “FURY”, if found in the given tweet, to “You are fired!” and “I am furious.”, respectively. If either word is not found or there are characters in tweet besides E, F, I, R, U, and Y, then “Fake tweet.” is returned. If “FIRE” appears more than once, then “and you” will be inserted between “You” and “are”. If “FURY” appears more than once, then “really” will be inserted between “am” and “furious.” The number of times these two substrings appear is equal to the number of times “FIRE” or “FURY” appears in tweet minus 1.

Parameters:

tweet – The input string representing a tweet by a former U.S. President that got mangled

Returns:

The President’s tweet after clearing up all the noise in tweet

This function finds the multiple for “Fizz” and the multiple for “Buzz”. For example, given [1, “Fizz”, “Buzz”, “Fizz”, 5, “FizzBuzz”], the function will return (2, 3). Note that “Fizz” or “Buzz” may not be present in the list, and the multiple for “Fizz” and the multiple for “Buzz” may be equal.

codewars.going_to_the_cinema module¶

Going to the Cinema

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.going_to_the_cinema.movie(card, ticket, percent)[source]¶

This function returns the number of times that John has to go to the cinema such that the price of buying tickets with a membership card will cost less than just buying tickets without one. With a membership card, the number of times that John goes to the cinema is the number of times the discount is applied to a ticket. For example, if the price of a ticket is $10, the discount for a ticket is 10%, and John goes to the cinema three times, then the total price of a ticket, including a membership card that costs $500, is 500 + 10 * (0.9 ^ 3) = $507.29.

Parameters:

  • card – The price for a membership card.

  • ticket – The price for a single ticket, with or without a membership card.

  • percent – The discount as a percentage applied to a ticket if one has a membership card.

Returns:

The number of times that John has to go to the cinema such that the total cost of a

membership card and tickets rounded up to the nearest dollar will cost less than just tickets.

codewars.gradebook module¶

Gradebook

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.gradebook.get_grade(arg_1: int, arg_2: int, arg_3: int) → str[source]¶

This function averages the given three grades and returns a grade letter. If the average is greater than or equal to 90 and less than or equal to 100, then “A” is returned. If the average is less than 90 and greater than or equal to 80, then “B” is returned. If the average is less than 80 and greater than or equal to 70, then “C” is returned. If the average is less than 70 and greater than or equal to 60, then “D” is returned. If the average is less than 60, then “F” is returned.

Parameters:

  • arg_1 – The first grade

  • arg_2 – The second grade

  • arg_3 – The third grade

Returns:

A grade letter representing the average of the three grades

codewars.how_many_urinals_are_free module¶

How Many Urinals Are Free

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.how_many_urinals_are_free.get_free_urinals(urinals: str) → int[source]¶

This function counts the number of urinals that can be used based on an unspoken rule that two urinals side by side cannot be occupied at the same time. A urinal can be used only if each side of it is unoccupied. An occupied urinal is represented by 1 in the binary string, and an unoccupied urinal is represented by 0. An occupied urinal cannot have another occupied urinal next to it, e.g. “11”. If this case is found, -1 is returned.

Parameters:

urinals – The input string, a binary string representing urinals that are occupied and unoccupied

Returns:

The number of urinals that can be used based on the unspoken rule, or -1 if two urinals are occupied and next to each other

codewars.isbn_10_validation module¶

ISBN-10 Validation

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.isbn_10_validation.valid_isbn10(isbn: str) → bool[source]¶

This function validates an ISBN 10 identifier, which is ten digits long. The first nine characters are digits 0-9. The last digit can be 0-9 or X whose value is 10.

An ISBN 10 identifier is valid if the sum of the digits multiplied by their position (starting with 1) modulo 11 equals zero.

Parameters:

isbn – The input string, the ISBN 10 identifier to validate

Returns:

True if the ISBN 10 identifier is valid, False otherwise

codewars.iterative_rotation_cipher module¶

Iterative Rotation Cipher

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.iterative_rotation_cipher.decode(string: str) → str[source]¶

This function decodes the given string that was encoded using encode(). To decode the string: 1. Get the number N to rotate the entire string and each word from the beginning of the string. 2. After removing the number and any leading whitespaces, rotate each word in the string to the left N times. 3. Strip off the spaces (not newline characters) between each word. 4. Rotate the entire string to the left N times. Steps 2 through 4 are repeated N times.

Parameters:

string – The input string to decode

Returns:

The decoded string

codewars.iterative_rotation_cipher.encode(number: int, string: str) → str[source]¶

This function encodes the given string using the following algorithm. 1. All spaces (not newline characters) are stripped off the string. 2. The entire string is rotated to the right number times. 3. The spaces are put back in the same positions. 4. Each word in the string is rotated to the right number times. Steps 1 through 4 are repeated number times.

Parameters:

  • number – The input integer, the number of times to rotate the entire string and each word

  • string – The input string to encode

Returns:

The encoded string

codewars.keyboard_handler module¶

Keyboard Handler

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.keyboard_handler.handler(key: str, is_caps: bool = False, is_shift: bool = False) → str[source]¶

This function returns a key from a QWERTY keyboard. If Caps Lock is on and Shift is not pressed, the uppercase version of an alphabet character is returned. If Caps Lock is off and Shift is pressed, the uppercase version of an alphabet character or a symbol from the shift_keys map is returned. If Caps Lock is on and Shift is pressed, the lowercase version of an alphabet character or a character from the shift_keys map is returned. If Caps Lock is off and Shift is not pressed, the key that was pressed is simply returned. If key is an uppercase letter, a string that contains two or more characters, or is not a string, the string “KeyError” is returned.

Parameters:

  • key – The key that was pressed on a QWERTY keyboard

  • is_caps – True if Caps Lock is on, False otherwise

  • is_shift – True if Shift is pressed at the same time as key, False otherwise

Returns:

A character or string as described above

codewars.keyword_cipher module¶

Keyword Cipher

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.keyword_cipher.keyword_cipher(msg: str, keyword: str)[source]¶

To encrypt msg, first drop all the letters in keyword that appear more than once. For example, if “wednesday” is the keyword, the result will be “wednsay”. Then the rest of the letters of the English alphabet that do not appear in keyword are appended to the end of the result, so the encryption key of the previous example will become “wednsaybcfghijklmopqrtuvxz”. Finally, the characters in msg will be substituted using a dict with characters of the English alphabet as the keys and the characters in the encryption key as the values. Characters such as numbers and symbols are left as is in the encrypted string.

Parameters:

  • msg – The message to encrypt

  • keyword – The string that is used to generate the encryption key

Returns:

An encrypted string

codewars.likes_vs_dislikes.like_or_dislike(lst: list)[source]¶

This function iterates through a list of buttons that were pressed and returns the final state. If the Like or Dislike button is pressed twice in a row, the current state will be Nothing. If an empty list is passed to the function, Nothing is returned. If the list contains only one button, the final state will be represented by that button. If the Like button is pressed and then the Dislike button is pressed, or vice versa, then the current state will be the last button that was pressed.

Parameters:

lst – A list of Like or Dislike buttons.

Returns:

Like, Dislike, or Nothing

This function validates that the given message is in the following format: length of word followed by word, length of word followed by word, etc. For example, given “3hey5hello2hi”, this function will return True because “hey” is 3 characters long, “hello” is 5 characters long, and “hi” is 2 characters long.

codewars.mexican_wave module¶

Mexican Wave

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.mexican_wave.wave(people: str) → list[str][source]¶

This function turns a string into a Mexican Wave. For example, given “hello”, this function will return [“Hello”, “hEllo”, “heLlo”, “helLo”, “hellO”]. If the string has spaces in between each word, they are ignored, and the next letter will be turned into uppercase. For example, given “It is”, this function will return [“It is”, “iT is”, “it Is”, “it iS”]. The uppercase letter represents a person standing up while the lowercase letters represent people sitting down.

Parameters:

people – The input string that represents people

Returns:

The string turned into a Mexican Wave as described above

  • selfie – True to apply the selfie and diagonal transformations

Returns:

codewars.numbers_of_letters_of_numbers module¶

Numbers of Letters of Numbers

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.numbers_of_letters_of_numbers.numbers_of_letters(number: int) → list[str][source]¶

This function converts each digit in number into a word, e.g. 99 becomes “ninenine”, and then adds the word to a list. Then it converts the length of the word into a word, e.g. “ninenine” has eight characters, so “ninenine” becomes “eight”, and adds the word to a list. This process of converting a word’s length into a word continues until the word starts to repeat. Then the list is returned. For example, given 99, a list containing “ninenine”, “eight”, “five”, and “four” is returned. Converting the length of “four” to a word also produces “four”, so the aforementioned list of four strings is returned.

Parameters:

number – The input integer

Returns:

A list of strings

This function converts the given list of integers (ASCII codes) into a list of dictionaries. The key will be an integer from the list as a string, and the value will be the character represented by the ASCII code. All integers in numbers are valid ASCII codes for lowercase characters.

Parameters:

numbers – The input list of integers

Returns:

A list of dictionaries

codewars.one_two_3_four_5 module¶

1 Two 3 Four 5

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.one_two_3_four_5.conv(num: int) → str[source]¶

This function converts the given number to a string of numbers and words using the following rules: if the length of the number is even, all odd digits are left as is, and all even digits are converted to words, e.g. “2” to “two”. The position of the digit is the length that the word must be, which means that the word is repeated until the length is reached. Each word in the string alternates between lowercase and uppercase (lowercase first). If the length of the number is odd, all even digits are left as is, all odd digits are converted to words, and the case for the words starts with uppercase.

Parameters:

num – The input integer

Returns:

A string containing numbers and words

codewars.one_two_3_four_5.num_to_word(number: str, length: int, lowercase_first: bool) → str[source]¶

This helper function converts the given number to a word, e.g. “1” to “one”. The word will be repeated until the length of the concatenated string is equal to or greater than length. If the length is greater than length, the string will be truncated up to length characters. The case of all characters in each word in the concatenated string will alternate between lowercase and uppercase, e.g. “oneONEone” and “TWOtwoTW”.

Parameters:

  • number – The number to convert to a word

  • length – The length of the concatenated string that is returned

  • lowercase_first – True if the case must start with lowercase first, False if the case must start with uppercase first

Returns:

A concatenated string containing one or more repeated words

codewars.pauls_misery module¶

Paul’s Misery

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.pauls_misery.paul(events: list[str]) → str[source]¶

This function determines whether Paul who likes to complete katas on Codewars is miserable. Each string in the given list is worth zero, one, five, or ten points. If his score (the sum of all the points) is above 100, he is miserable. If his score is greater than or equal to 70 and less than 100, he is sad. If his score is greater than or equal to 40 and less than 70, he is happy. Finally, if his score is below 40, he is super happy.

Parameters:

events – The input list of strings representing events in Paul’s life

Returns:

“Super happy!”, “Happy!”, “Sad!”, or “Miserable!”

codewars.playing_with_passphrases module¶

Playing with Passphrases

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.playing_with_passphrases.play_pass(string: str, num: int)[source]¶

This function generates a secure passphrase by performing the following in order: shift right each alphabetic character by the given number, replace each digit by its complement to nine, keep all non-alphanumeric characters, lowercase all alphabetic characters that are in an odd position in the string, uppercase all alphabetic characters that are in an even position, and finally reverse the string.

Parameters:

  • string – The input string from which to generate a passphrase

  • num – The number to shift right each alphabetic character

Returns:

A passphrase

codewars.prize_draw module¶

Prize Draw

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.prize_draw.rank(participants: str, weights: list[int], winner_rank: int) → str[source]¶

This function returns the name of the person with the winning number at position winner_rank in the list of participants. The winning number is calculated as follows: sum the letters of a participant’s name (letters A-Z represent numbers 1-26), add the length of the participant’s name to the sum, and multiply the result by a weight in weights to get the winning number. The participants are sorted in descending order by winning numbers, but if two or more winning numbers are the same, those participants are sorted in alphabetical order. indexes in the list of participants with winning numbers start at 1.

Parameters:

  • participants – The input list of strings

  • weights – The input list of integers

  • winner_rank – The input integer representing the position in the list of winning participants

Returns:

The name of the participant at position winner_rank after calculating all the winning numbers and sorting the results

codewars.reverse_or_rotate module¶

Reverse or Rotate?

Author: BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.reverse_or_rotate.revrot(string: str, size: int) → str[source]¶

This function divides a string that represents an integer into chunks of size size. If the sum of cube of each digit in a chunk is an even number, the chunk will be reversed. Otherwise, the chunk will be rotated to the left one digit. If the last chunk is not of size size, it is ignored. If size is zero or greater than the length of the string, or the string is empty or None, an empty string is returned. Finally, the chunks are concatenated together into a single string.

Parameters:

  • string – The input string representing an integer

  • size – The input integer, the size of each chunk

Returns:

A concatenated string with each chunk either reversed or rotated

ROT13

codewars.rot13.rot13(string: str) → str[source]¶

This function shifts all the alphabet (A through Z) characters in string to the right 13 times, wrapping around to the beginning if the end is reached. Other characters such as numbers and symbols are left alone.

string – The input string

codewars.rot13.shift_character(char: str, offset: int) → str[source]¶

This helper function shifts the character char to the right 13 times after first subtracting offset. Because the ASCII code for lowercase a and uppercase A do not start at 0, offset has to be subtracted from the ASCII value of char. After the shift is applied, offset is added back.

Parameters:

  • char – The character to shift

  • offset – The offset

Returns:

A character

codewars.rotate_for_a_max module¶

Rotate for a Max

Author: BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.rotate_for_a_max.max_rot(number: int) → int[source]¶

This function rotates a digit starting from the far left to the left one digit all the way until the last digit on the far right is reached. For example, given “1234”, this function will perform the following rotations: “2341”, “2413”, and “2431”. Finally, the maximum out of all the numbers (which include the original number–in the example, “1234”) is returned (in the example, “2431” is the maximum).

Parameters:

number – The input integer

Returns:

The maximum that is produced after rotating each digit

codewars.simple_encryption_number_1_alternating_split module¶

Simple Encryption #1: Alternating Split

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.simple_encryption_number_1_alternating_split.decrypt(ciphertext: str, num: int) → str[source]¶

This function decrypts the given ciphertext by first finding the midpoint in the ciphertext. Next, a character from the midpoint is added to an empty list, then a character from the beginning of the string is added. Then the next character after the midpoint is added to the list followed by the next character after the first character in the string. This process is repeated until the end of the string and the midpoint are reached.

Parameters:

  • ciphertext – The input string to decrypt

  • num – The number of times to repeat the aforementioned process

Returns:

A plaintext, or the ciphertext if the string is empty or num is less than or equal to zero

codewars.simple_encryption_number_1_alternating_split.encrypt(plaintext: str, num: int) → str[source]¶

This function encrypts the given plaintext by taking all the characters at odd indexes in the plaintext and concatenating them with all the characters at even indexes in the same plaintext. This process is repeated num times.

Parameters:

  • plaintext – The input string to encrypt

  • num – The number of times to repeat the concatenation process

Returns:

A ciphertext, or the plaintext if the string is empty or num is less than or equal to zero

codewars.simple_encryption_number_1_alternating_split.take_chars(text: str, even: bool = True) → str[source]¶

This helper function produces a string using the characters at even indexes in text if even is True. If even is False, the characters at odd indexes are used to produce a new string.

Parameters:

  • text – The input string

  • even – True to use the characters at even indexes in text to produce a new string, False to use characters at odd indexes

Returns:

A new string using characters from text

codewars.simple_encryption_number_4_qwerty.shift(text: str, key: int, should_encrypt: bool = True) → str[source]¶

This helper function rotates characters in the given string right (to encrypt, i.e. if should_encrypt is True) or left (to decrypt, i.e. if should_encrypt is False). The value for key is between 000 and 999, inclusive. Each digit in key represents one region and the number of steps to rotate each character in text that belongs to that region. The case of each character is preserved, i.e. encrypting an uppercase character in text will produce an uppercase character in the ciphertext.

Parameters:

  • text – The input string to encrypt or decrypt

  • key – The key, between 000 and 999, inclusive, each digit representing one region and the number of steps to rotate each character in that region

  • should_encrypt – True to encrypt, False to decrypt (default is True)

Returns:

A ciphertext or plaintext

codewars.simple_fun_number_137_s2n module¶

Simple Fun #137: S2N

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.simple_fun_number_137_s2n.s2n(base_limit: int, exp_limit: int) → int[source]¶

This function finds the sum for the range 0 to base_limit, inclusive, for all exponents from 0 to exp_limit, inclusive. For example, if base_limit is 2 and exp_limit is 3, the function will perform the following sum: (0^0 + 0^1 + 0^2 + 0^3) + (1^0 + 1^1 + 1^2 + 1^3) + (2^0 + 2^1 + 2^2 + 2^3) = 20

Parameters:

  • exp_limit – The input integer, the last exponent in the range

Returns:

The sum from 0 to base_limit, inclusive, for all exponents from 0 to exp_limit, inclusive

codewars.simple_fun_number_149_next_day_of_week module¶

Simple Fun #149: Next Day of Week

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.simple_fun_number_149_next_day_of_week.next_day_of_week(current_day: int, available_week_days: int) → int[source]¶

This function finds the next day of the current week that an alarm will sound. If the alarm will not sound for the remainder of the week, the first day of the next week for which the alarm is configured is returned. Each bit that is turned on in available_week_days represents a day that the alarm will sound. It is assumed that an alarm will sound at least once in a week.

Parameters:

  • current_day – The current day (today)

  • available_week_days – An integer whose bits in the binary representation represent days of a week

Returns:

The next day that the alarm will sound (0 is Sunday, 7 is Saturday)

codewars.simple_fun_number_194_binary_string module¶

Binary String

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.simple_fun_number_194_binary_string.bin_str(binary_string: str) → int[source]¶

This function counts the number of steps needed to turn a binary string into a string containing all zeros. If a one is found in the binary string, all the bits to the right of the one and including the one is flipped, i.e. one becomes zero, and vice versa. For example, given “0101”, the function will return 3 because “0101” -> “0010” -> “0001” -> “0000”.

Parameters:

binary_string – The binary string representation of a number

Returns:

The number of steps needed to turn the binary string into one that contains all zeros

codewars.simple_pig_latin module¶

Simple Pig Latin

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.simple_pig_latin.pig_it(text: str) → str[source]¶

This function returns the Pig Latin version of text. In Pig Latin, the first letter of a word and “ay” are appended to the end of the word. For example, “Hello” -> “elloHay”. Punctuation are left in place if they are at the end of the word. For example, “Hello!!!” -> “elloHay!!!”.

Parameters:

Returns:

The Pig Latin version of text

codewars.simple_string_expansion module¶

Simple String Expansion

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.simple_string_expansion.solve(string: str) → str[source]¶

This function expands a string given its shortened form. For example, given “3(b(2(c)))”, this function will return “bccbccbcc”. Step by step, this function does the following: 3(b(2(c))) -> 3(b(cc)) -> 3(bcc) -> bccbccbcc.

Parameters:

string – The input string

Returns:

The expanded form of string

codewars.slope_of_a_line module¶

Slope of a Line

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.slope_of_a_line.get_slope(point_1: list, point_2: list)[source]¶

This function calculates the slope of a line. If the X values for both points are the same or point_1 and point_2 refer to the same point, None is returned. Otherwise, the slope is returned. The slope is the difference of the two Y values divided by the difference of the two X values.

Parameters:

  • point_1 – A list that represents the first point and contains two values, X and Y.

  • point_2 – A list that represents the second point and contains two values, X and Y.

Returns:

The slope.

This function calculates the Stanton measure of a list. The Stanton measure is calculated by counting the number of times that the number 1 appears in the list and then counting the number of times the count appears in the list. For example, given [1, 2, 3, 2, 1, 2, 5, 2], the Stanton measure is 4.

The Stanton measure of arr

codewars.substring_fun module¶

Substring Fun

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.substring_fun.nth_char(words: list[str]) → str[source]¶

This function creates a string from the given list of strings. A letter from each string in the list is used to create the string, and the index of a string in the list is used to extract a letter from that string. For example, given [“yoda”, “best”, “has”], “yes” will be returned, because words[0][0] + words[1][1] + words[2][2] = “yes”.

Parameters:

words – The input list of strings

Returns:

A string created from one letter of each string in words

codewars.tap_code_translation module¶

Tap Code Translation

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.tap_code_translation.tap_code_translation(text: str) → str[source]¶

This function turns the given string of lowercase ASCII letters into a string containing dots and spaces. All instances of ‘k’ will be replaced by ‘c’ before the translation takes place. Each character in text will be converted to one or more dots, separated by a space, and finally followed by one or more dots. The first set of dots represents the index of the row (starting from 1) in a 2-dimensional list in which the character is found, and the second set of dots represents the index of the column (also starting from 1) in which the character is found. Finally, each translated character is separated by a space in the string that is returned.

Parameters:

text – The input string containing lowercase ASCII letters

Returns:

A string containing a series of dots and spaces

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

This function determines whether an employee should be fired or commended. If the sum of all the other employees’ happiness divided by all the employees in meeting is less than or equal to 5, then the employee is fired. Otherwise, the employee is commended. A boss is also in meeting, and their happiness level counts twice.

  • boss – The name of the boss who may or may not be in the meeting

Returns:

codewars.thinkful_list_and_loop_drills_grade_calculator.calculate_grade(scores: list) → str[source]¶

This function calculates the average grade for the given list of grades. If the grade is greater than or equal to 90% and less than or equal to 100%, ‘A’ is returned. If the grade is less than 90% and greater than or equal to 80%, ‘B’ is returned. If the grade is less than 80% and greater than or equal to 70%, ‘C’ is returned. If the grade is less than 70% and greater than or equal to 60%, ‘D’ is returned. Finally, if the grade is below 60%, ‘F’ is returned.

Parameters:

scores – The input list of grades

Returns:

A letter grade based on the aforementioned formula

search(word: str) → bool[source]¶

Searches the dictionary for the given word. If the regular expression does not contain a period, an exact match is performed. Periods mean “match any character”. For example, given “.ad” and the dictionary contains [dad, mad, sad, eat, sun, bunny], True will be returned because “dad”, “mad”, and “sad” match that pattern.

Parameters:

word – The word to search for

Returns:

plaintext – The plaintext to encode

Returns:

A ciphertext

codewars.vin_checker module¶

VIN Checker

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.vin_checker.check_vin(number: str) → bool[source]¶

This function checks whether the given VIN is valid. A vehicle identification number (VIN) must be seventeen characters long. If ‘I’, ‘O’, or ‘Q’ appears in the VIN, it is invalid. Each alphabetic character in the VIN is converted to a number. Then each number is multiplied by a weight. All the products are summed together. The modulus 11 of the sum is taken. If the ninth character in the VIN is an ‘X’, the result of the modulus operation must be 10. Otherwise, the result of the modulus operation must be equal to the ninth character. If they are not equal, the VIN is invalid.

Parameters:

number – A string representing a valid or invalid VIN

Returns:

True if the VIN is valid, False otherwise

codewars.volume_of_a_cuboid module¶

Volume of a Cuboid

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.volume_of_a_cuboid.get_volume_of_cuboid(length, width, height)[source]¶

This function returns the volume of a cuboid, which is length * width * height.

Parameters:

  • length – The length of a cuboid

  • width – The width of a cuboid

  • height – The height of a cuboid

Returns:

The volume of a cuboid

codewars.vowel_shifting module¶

Vowel Shifting

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.vowel_shifting.vowel_shift(text: str, num: int) → str[source]¶

This function rotates all the vowels in the given string right if num is positive or left if num is negative. The other characters in the string are left in place. For example, given “This is a test!” and num is 3, “This as e tist!” is returned because [i, i, a, e] rotated three steps to the right is [i, a, e, i].

Parameters:

  • text – The input string

  • num – The number of steps to rotate vowels right (if positive) or left (if negative)

Returns:

A new string after rotating all the vowels right or left, or the same string if text is empty or num is zero

codewars.vowels_back module¶

Vowel Back

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.vowels_back.move_letter(letter: str, shift: int, backward: bool) → str[source]¶

This helper function shifts the given letter either left (backward is True) or right shift places.

Parameters:

  • letter – The letter to shift

  • shift – The number of places to shift left (backward) or right (forward)

  • backward – True to shift left, False to shift right

Returns:

The result of the shift, or the original letter if the result is ‘c’, ‘o’, ‘d’, or ‘e’

codewars.vowels_back.vowel_back(string: str) → str[source]¶

This function shifts all the letters in the given string forward or backward based on the following rules: move consonants nine places forward, move vowels five places backward. Wrap around to the beginning or end of the alphabet if the shift goes past ‘z’ or ‘a’, respectively. Exceptions: if the character to shift is ‘c’ or ‘o’, move backward one place; if the character is ‘d’, move backward three places, and if the character is ‘e’, move backward four places. If the result of the shift results in ‘c’, ‘o’, ‘d’, or ‘e’, revert back to the original letter.

Parameters:

string – The input string that contains characters to shift forward or backward

Returns:

A new string that contains characters that were the result of a shift

codewars.weight_for_weight module¶

Weight for Weight

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.weight_for_weight.order_weight(string: str) → str[source]¶

This function sorts the given list of weights by the sum of all the digits in each weight. If two weights are the same, then the two are sorted in lexicographical order, i.e. each weight is treated as a string not an int when it comes to sorting equal weights.

Parameters:

string – The input string representing weights

Returns:

A string of weights sorted according to the description above

codewars.well_of_ideas_easy_version module¶

Well of Ideas: Easy Version

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.well_of_ideas_easy_version.well(arr: list[str]) → str[source]¶

This function counts the number of times the word “good” appears in the given list of strings. If it appears once or twice, “Publish!” is returned. If it appears more than two times, the string “I smell a series!” is returned. But if it does not appear in the list at all, “Fail!” is returned.

Parameters:

arr – The input list of strings

Returns:

“I smell a series!”, “Publish!” or “Fail!”

codewars.well_of_ideas_harder_version module¶

Well of Ideas: Harder Version

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.well_of_ideas_harder_version.well(ideas: list[list]) → str[source]¶

This function counts the number of times the word “good” (regardless of case) appears in the given two-dimensional list. Each list may contain not just strings but also other types of values such as integers and floats. If the word appears once or twice, “Publish!” is returned. If it appears more than two times, the string “I smell a series!” is returned. But if it does not appear at all, “Fail!” is returned.

Parameters:

ideas – The input list of strings

Returns:

“I smell a series!”, “Publish!” or “Fail!”

codewars.what_a_classy_song module¶

What a Classy Song

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

class codewars.what_a_classy_song.Song(title: str, artist: str)[source]¶

Bases: object

This class represents a song that is sung by an artist. A set in this class keeps track of the people who listened to a song.

how_many(listeners: list[str]) → int[source]¶

Returns the number of people who listened to this song in a day. Each call to this method represents a day. Only unique listeners are counted throughout the lifetime of this song. For example, “John” and “JOHN” are considered the same person, but “John” and “Johnny” are two different people.

Parameters:

listeners – A list representing people who listened to this song

Returns:

The number of people who listened to this song in a day

codewars.whats_the_real_floor module¶

What is the Real Floor?

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.whats_the_real_floor.get_real_floor(floor: int) → int[source]¶

This function returns the real floor of a building. In the United States, the first floor is actually the ground floor, and there is no thirteenth floor. If floor is between 1 and 12, inclusive, then floor - 1 is returned. If floor is greater than 13, then floor - 2 is returned. Basements (negatives) stay the same.

Parameters:

floor – The input integer representing the floor of a building in the United States

Returns:

The real floor of the building

This function returns True if number is prime and also a Wilson prime. Note that the only Wilson primes that exist are 5, 13, and 563. If any other Wilson primes exist, they must be larger than 2 * 10^13, or 20,000,000,000,000.

codewars.word_mesh module¶

Word Mesh

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.word_mesh.word_mesh(words: str) → str[source]¶

This function returns a string in which the characters represent substrings that are at the end of one word in the given list of words and begin with the next word in the list. For example, given “cat attack kitchen engrave”, the function will return “atken” (“at”, “k”, and “en”). If there are no substrings at the end of one word that appear at the beginning of the next word, “failed to mesh” is returned.

Parameters:

words – A space-delimited list of words

Returns:

A string that contains substrings, or “failed to mesh”

This function converts each word in words, delimited by whitespace character(s), to a hexadecimal string that represents a color. A list of hexadecimal values, each representing a color

codewars.yoga_class module¶

Yoga Class

Author:

BJ Peter Dela Cruz

codewars.yoga_class.yoga(classroom: list[list[int]], poses: list[int]) → int[source]¶

This function returns the total number of students who can complete a yoga pose in the given list of poses. A student can complete a pose if the sum of the skill levels of all the students in the row that contains the student and the student’s skill level is equal to or greater than the skill level of the pose.

Parameters:

  • classroom – The input list of list of integers, each row representing students in a classroom

  • poses – The input list of integers, each representing the skill level needed to accomplish a pose

Returns:

The sum of all students who can accomplish each pose in the list of poses
